      <hedline>
        <hl1>On Campus, Diversity or Unity?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by John C Gulla, head of Blake School in Minneapolis, says Arthur Levine's June 11 Op-Ed analysis of campus balkanization indirectly illustrates paradox facing selective schools, whether to promote community or diversity (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Arthur Levine's analysis of the current tendency toward campus balkanization (Op-Ed, June 11) indirectly illustrates one of the great paradoxes faced by all selective educational institutions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Arthur Levine's analysis of the current tendency toward campus balkanization (Op-Ed, June 11) indirectly illustrates one of the great paradoxes faced by all selective educational institutions.</p>
        <p>As we strive to achieve diversity in our schools, so, too, do we simultaneously endeavor to create a strong sense of ''community,'' certainly a runner-up to ''diversity'' as the word most frequently heard on school campuses. Many see the two goals as mutually exclusive. Others, myself included, see this dialectic to be as basic to our work in education as our country's motto, ''E Pluribus Unum,'' is to the work of the nation.</p>
        <p>JOHN C. GULLA  Head of School, Blake School  Minneapolis, June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
